I've switch from using microns to fountain pens on my art.

snippet.textDisplay: So the reason why the ink spread during erasing is due to either the ink not fully drying (which you said it had) or the paper not being compatable with that particular ink. Some papers take fountain pen ink better than others. But since this looked like a not great inexpensive ink and glass pen set (none of the well known ink companies would put out a bottle with terrible text like "a hippopotamus is a hippopotamus") it could be a fault of the ink itself. With a decent ink from one of the better known brands, you should be able to erase pencil after the ink dries.
snippet.textOriginal: So the reason why the ink spread during erasing is due to either the ink not fully drying (which you said it had) or the paper not being compatable with that particular ink. Some papers take fountain pen ink better than others. But since this looked like a not great inexpensive ink and glass pen set (none of the well known ink companies would put out a bottle with terrible text like "a hippopotamus is a hippopotamus") it could be a fault of the ink itself. snippet.textDisplay: Fountain pen people who are more into collecting inks than pens will often use these to test and swatch their ink collection. Using it with a different kind of ink that is quick drying and doesn't smear would solve your problem. You could look at recommendations for lefty fountain pen users to find those. And fraud-proof inks will even survive watercolor without getting everywhere. ETA: You can also use it for pigments derived from natural sources like tea, if you were so inclined, since you don't have to worry about damage to brush bristles or corrosion of a metal nib.
snippet.textOriginal: Fountain pen people who are more into collecting inks than pens will often use these to test and swatch their ink collection. Using it with a different kind of ink that is quick drying and doesn't smear would solve your problem. You could look at recommendations for lefty fountain pen users to find those.
